	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				If you think about it...what can REALLY be said about this?<BR>
<BR>
Nothing.<BR>
<BR>
Without having walked in this &quot;kids&quot; shoes you cant blame him. Without walking in his mothers shoes you cant blame her. And since it's impossible to do the proverbial walk in anyone shoes....you just never know.<BR>
<BR>
We all have reasons for the actions and reactions of the many thousands of things we do in a days time and yeah we might want to blame the mom for not doing enough or blame the &quot;kid&quot; because he just had issues to begin with, again...<BR>
<BR>
you just never know.<BR>
<BR>
To be quite honest, that's about all I can say concerning this particular incident.<BR>
<BR>
What I CAN comment on, with some certainty, is the attack on the game for being &quot;addictive&quot;. Yes, like many many many things in the world this game is addictive and to lay the blame on Sony for this kids addiction is, to be quite honest, a load.<BR>
<BR>
Most things fun ARE addictive. Should every company and/or organization be held accountable when you have fun??? Boy, wouldnt THAT suck! What we do is manage our fun.<BR>
<BR>
Like the guy said in Gladiator; &quot;Sometimes I do what I want to do...the rest of the time I do what I have to.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In the case of all things &quot;fun&quot;, we try to make time for them and enjoy them while we can (in moderation) but not at the expense of other things we have to do.<BR>
<BR>
If you enjoy doing something, say, playing EverQuest then thier is no harm in that. If you spend every available moment on the game then thats fine to (some people might spend SOME of those available moments going for a walk or reading a book...but no matter) if you spend not only available moments on the game but also moments that really should not be resreved for the game (doing laundry, taking a shower, going to work, spending time with the wife/husband and kids) then you have....<BR>
<BR>
drum roll please...<BR>
<BR>
A PROBLEM.<BR>
<BR>
Your &quot;fun&quot; has become an addiction. With addictions come other side effects that may lead to health issues or even mental issues.<BR>
<BR>
I dont know. Just rambling I suppose. Anyway, I find many many people on EQ have an addiction to the game. Some just play for fun when they can. Its only a matter of time before those with an addiction suffer for it.<BR>
<BR>
This &quot;kid&quot; was only the first in a long line of drowning addicts.<BR>
<BR>
Will you be next? Who can say? Only you. Again, I cant walk in your shoes.<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
