	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I wrote a paper for a class a few weeks ago that shows how I feel.  outsiders jsut don't understand...maby if the mother had cared more she would have sat down and played with him.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The little things<BR>
<BR>
The quest<BR>
<BR>
I have a little part of my life that has affected my life in a big way. Everquest, the bane to my social life:  it allows me to escape into a fantasy world where the people are nice.  I play with or against over five hundred thousand other people just like me in a world where we can put ourselves behind a mask of technology.  &#8220;It is just a game,&#8221; they say.  But &#8220;they&#8221; have never played it long enough to make friends you can call family.  &#8220;They&#8221; haven&#8217;t spent over ten thousand hours leveling a character and building his gear in a world that if you want to be strong you are, and if you want to be wise you are.  There is nothing that you cannot be or cannot do.  Imagine if the real world was so grand.  No one cares what you look like, just how you think.  It is a paradise for the panderers who prefer sitting and thinking over running and breathing.  Why is that the standard? Why are you not &#8220;cool&#8221; or popular because you scored a 5 on your AP tests, but you are if you are on the starting line up of the homecoming game?  If makes no sense that things are how they are.  I suppose it all depends on what everyone wants to get out of life.  In my opinion all human beings should strive to better our race, to ensure that in ten thousand years we humans will still be the dominant species on this planet and on other distant heavens.  <BR>
<BR>
Think back to your youth, bringing home an A on your spelling test in the 4th grade and how your parents were proud of you.  Gave you a feeling of accomplishment and self-satisfaction when you parents congratulated you.  Now, imagine getting that feeling every hour of every day.  As you kill the creature that should have torn your heard off with it&#8217;s claws and feasted on you sinew.  Seeing your experience bar move up as you hone your combat skills.  One more step closer to the beloved DING announcing your advancement to the whole world, and then the accompanying cries or congratulations from everyone who hears.  Everyone is proud of you and everyone is glad for you.  A rush of joy washes over you more powerful then any drug when your guild leader asks you to join them in the plane of fear to slay the avatar of an evil god that plagues the world with suffering.<BR>
<BR>
I said it is a bane to my social life and that is what it is.  Why live in a world as flawed as ours when there is one so much greater just waiting to be played?  My friends wonder where I am at nights and my family misses my company.  I tell them that all they have to do to be with me is log on and we can have an adventure together far better then any that could be fathomed on the corporeal world. Alas they don&#8217;t see my wisdom.  They don&#8217;t even try to see the world through my eyes. They are as empathic as rocks and as wise as a gravestone.  The fools say that games are for children and that is why they won&#8217;t try it.  Games are for the wise that want to better their intellectual selves.  For children they say&#8230;tell that to the leader of my guild, my family in the game.  I am the youngest on in it out of the hundred and fifty odd people.  The leaders are a married couple in their late forties.  When I tell this to my father he says that they have wasted their lives, but he is oblivious to the fact that the own a drafting firm that basically runs itself and that is how they can afford to spend so much time in my realm.  My father, HA! Like his life is somehow better.  Even if my friends on Everquest didn&#8217;t have jobs, weren&#8217;t rich, WHO CARES!  My father goes to work every week in a job he hates, and comes home angry every time.  In my opinion being unsuccessfully financially but being happy with your life if a far greater accomplishment than having wealth but no joy to go with it.<BR>
<BR>
With those words we depart.  If you have not learned about who I am yet then you did not think; you read the words but did not hear their meanings.  The essence of my being has been poured into these pages for you to take in.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
